{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642892"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:45:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:45:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17966"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17966"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.36,0.08,0.08,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10680"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64560"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7197"},{"type":"tags","id":"7266"},{"type":"tags","id":"7272"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is primarily responsible for pulling the corners of the mouth laterally during smiling?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Risorius","Levator anguli oris","Buccinator","Orbicularis oris","Zygomaticus major"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erisorius\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is responsible for pulling the corners of the mouth laterally, contributing to the expression of a smile. It is a superficial muscle of facial expression that originates from the fascia over the parotid gland and inserts into the skin at the angle of the mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezygomaticus major\u003C/strong\u003E also plays a role in smiling by elevating the corners of the mouth, but it pulls them upwards rather than laterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebuccinator\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is involved in compressing the cheek against the teeth and is important for actions like blowing and chewing, rather than smiling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eorbicularis oris\u003C/strong\u003E encircles the mouth and is responsible for actions such as puckering the lips, not lateral movement of the mouth corners.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elevator anguli oris\u003C/strong\u003E elevates the angle of the mouth, contributing to smiling, but does not primarily pull the corners laterally.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The risorius muscle is involved in facial expression, specifically in pulling the corners of the mouth laterally.","The risorius is innervated by the facial nerve, which is responsible for motor control of facial muscles."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"re